WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.177 --> 00:00:17.591
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:17.831 --> 00:00:20.028
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:20.277 --> 00:00:23.145
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:23.316 --> 00:00:26.598
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:26.903 --> 00:00:29.625
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:54.020 --> 00:00:56.260
Goran, good afternoon.
-Good afternoon.

00:00:56.540 --> 00:01:00.460
Thank you for being
a guest on our show.

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:07.940
Many famous people from the world
of sports have been guests on this show.

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:12.620
In fact, all who have been guests were
greats and had excellent careers.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:19.261
However, I can't remember the last time
someone at their peak,

00:01:19.976 --> 00:01:22.344
a global star like you,
was a guest.

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:26.900
And that's why I thank you on behalf
of the entire team. How are you?

00:01:27.380 --> 00:01:31.980
How are you spending your time after
Đoković and that situation with Rybakina?

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:38.940
Tell us more about it.
-Now I'm on forced vacation again.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:43.582
Thank you for inviting me to the show.
This is the first time I've had

00:01:43.663 --> 00:01:45.983
an interview with someone
who isn't a journalist.

00:01:46.074 --> 00:01:48.550
I hope it will be interesting.

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:53.260
And we both come from
the world of sports.

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:59.111
It was a bit strange. I don't want to
talk about it much, but I can say

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:02.780
it's a sad and strange story.

00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:08.577
She was the best female tennis player
in the world to me even before

00:02:09.046 --> 00:02:13.087
I became her coach. -The best.
-Because she plays the most

00:02:13.404 --> 00:02:18.681
beautiful and simplest game.
And I really enjoyed the job.

00:02:19.061 --> 00:02:25.712
Unfortunately, some things happened
off the court that I couldn't control,

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:29.747
and I didn't want to be a part of it
or part of that story.

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:34.660
I decided it was best
for me to step down.

00:02:35.140 --> 00:02:40.380
I wish her all the best in her career.
She will always be in the top five

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:45.380
or top ten best female players.
But it was a good experience.

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:50.780
I never thought I would be
a female coach, and I really liked it.

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:57.420
I don't know if I'll coach women again,
but after Novak and after that

00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:02.420
long ten-month break...
-You miss your job. -It was interesting.

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:07.780
That means you fell in love with coaching,
which is the same in every sport.

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:14.340
Does coaching make up for what you
had during your playing career?

00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:19.020
And that's the adrenaline, pressure,
responsibility, importance. -Yes.

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:22.340
I always thought I could be a good coach,
primarily because I had coaches

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:25.500
I could learn from.

00:03:25.900 --> 00:03:31.100
From the beginning of my career,
later from my coaches Mr. Niko Pilić,

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:36.700
Balaš Taroci, Vedran,
with whom I trained the longest.

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:43.020
The late Bob Brett, who taught me a lot.
So, I realized I could do that one day.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:47.260
However, after my career ended,
I wasn't ready yet.

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:53.740
I had to take a four or five - year break
to prove to myself I was ready.

00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:56.220
The beginning was good.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:04:04.340
It all started with Čilić and his
Grand Slam win at the US Open.

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.460
Then came Tomaš Berdych,
then Miloš Raonić.

00:04:07.780 --> 00:04:15.500
And then, the best tennis player of all
time, with whom I worked for five years.

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:19.540
It was turbulent, interesting,
and incredible to work with him.

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:25.060
Yes, exactly that...
I've known you for a long time.

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:28.660
We're about the same age
and from the same city.

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:32.140
We have mutual friends,
we hung out and went out together.

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:35.740
You surprised me when you
decided to become a coach.

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:38.700
You said several times
that you believed in it.

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:41.940
That you could convey ideas
and knowledge.

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:45.940
And you knew you would succeed.

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:50.700
You also said you were
challenged as a coach.

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:54.620
A priori, before you even started,
there was a lot of distrust.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:05:01.460
But you cleared up all doubts
by winning 12 Grand Slams

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:06.213
with Đoković and Čilić.
Tell us a little...

00:05:06.656 --> 00:05:16.622
As a coach, I'm interested in how
a coach in tennis can change the game.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:24.340
I'm not thinking about physical
or psychological preparation.

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:30.492
But how can you change
the way Đoković hits the ball,

00:05:30.717 --> 00:05:33.945
who you yourself say is the best
tennis player in the world?

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:36.270
And one of the best athletes.

00:05:36.377 --> 00:05:40.226
And he was the best player
even before you became his coach.

00:05:40.496 --> 00:05:43.475
How did you manage
to convince him of that?

00:05:43.714 --> 00:05:46.794
First, let me say something
about that distrust.

00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:51.539
I don't know why it was always like that,
maybe it's because of my facial expression.

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:54.540
But I always had to prove myself,
first as a tennis player,

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:57.060
and later as a coach.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:02.135
Someone can like me or not,
but I have results behind me

00:06:02.695 --> 00:06:04.894
that no one can dispute.

00:06:05.750 --> 00:06:12.315
I think I'm a slightly different type
of coach. You're involved in a team sport,

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:17.260
and when you enter the locker room,
there are 30 ego maniacs,

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:20.380
maybe more or less.

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:24.660
And you have to control all of them.
Tennis is an individual sport.

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:27.940
In fact, it's a gladiatorial sport,
but there's no contact.

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:30.940
Every day you have to give
300% of yourself.

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:34.900
No one asks about your health
or if you even want to play.

00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:40.820
And when you come to
a genius like Novak,

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:45.780
whose rule is that what was good today
is no longer good tomorrow.

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:49.380
The next day everything
has to be better.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:54.820
Something better is always sought.
I'm not for always changing things.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:59.540
But for making the best possible
use of what you have.

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:05.780
It's true that we worked on improving
the second and first serve,

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:10.060
on the accuracy of those serves.

00:07:11.020 --> 00:07:15.140
On being a little more aggressive.
On positioning at the net.

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:18.260
But those are all things...

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:24.180
You train something that you
might play during a match.

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:26.300
People don't understand that.

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:30.380
It rarely happens that what we train
happens during a match.

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:34.100
You can never organize training
to look like a match.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.420
No. -That's impossible.

00:07:36.513 --> 00:07:38.376
Training is training,
but a match is a match.

00:07:38.515 --> 00:07:40.360
And we have the same
problem in football.

00:07:41.660 --> 00:07:47.940
People always go back to the old ways
when there's a difficult situation.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:53.980
It seems to me that Federer said:
'I don't play against an opponent,

00:07:54.220 --> 00:07:56.140
I play against the ball.'

00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:00.060
Because that's how he understood it.

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:03.700
Everyone has their own
way of dealing with it...

00:08:03.798 --> 00:08:06.278
Why are the best players the best?
Why was Federer the best?

00:08:06.495 --> 00:08:10.615
Why was Novak the best?
Because he's flesh and blood too.

00:08:10.848 --> 00:08:15.082
He said his stomach hurts
before every match,

00:08:15.339 --> 00:08:19.300
that he's nervous, and he's
nervous during the match.

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:23.620
But I notice that. -Because
you were a tennis player too.

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:32.479
But nervousness affects
the opponent, not him.

00:08:32.992 --> 00:08:35.352
He's always at his level.

00:08:36.420 --> 00:08:39.420
He always comes out on top,
that's why he's the best.

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:45.340
There's a ranking of people who handle
nervousness and pressure better.

00:08:45.660 --> 00:08:50.150
Who handle those things better.
He's simply like that.

00:08:50.352 --> 00:08:54.369
He's one of a kind, such a player
appears once in 100,000 years.

00:08:54.714 --> 00:08:59.924
But he had two players
who were healthy competition.

00:09:00.176 --> 00:09:05.166
Roger, Rafael, and Nole became better
players because of that competition.

00:09:06.419 --> 00:09:10.416
It was a triangle of three
who helped each other.

00:09:10.734 --> 00:09:18.448
First, there were those two,
then came a guy I knew from 14.

00:09:19.580 --> 00:09:28.340
And he disrupted their Western theory.
So, it all fell apart for them.

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:33.700
From his father, who helped him...

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:39.220
Despite all the illogical things
that happened, he became the best.

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:49.030
It's true we work on those things,
but can you realize them in a match?

00:09:49.819 --> 00:09:52.379
He won those Grand Slams.

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:58.300
He improved his serve,
his game at the net.

00:09:59.260 --> 00:10:03.460
Novak always had a good serve,
but people didn't talk much about it.

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:08.300
They talked more about
his movement on the court.

00:10:11.643 --> 00:10:19.934
It's important to establish
a system with the player.

00:10:20.586 --> 00:10:22.786
Trust. That he trusts you.

00:10:23.262 --> 00:10:26.364
Because if he doesn't believe
in what I'm saying,

00:10:26.770 --> 00:10:31.090
or if I don't believe it
and he notices, there's no point.

00:10:31.361 --> 00:10:37.121
It's the same in team sports.
-I can pack my things and leave.

00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:43.660
Being his coach for five years is like
coaching Real Madrid, isn't it?

00:10:43.829 --> 00:10:46.869
That's what I told him when
he asked me to be his coach.

00:10:47.060 --> 00:10:50.086
It's like when someone from Real Madrid
calls and asks if you want to coach.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:52.340
Of course, I agreed.

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:58.380
I'll just tell my family at home
that I'm in Madrid. -That's right.

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:01.580
He's an institution.

00:11:02.100 --> 00:11:05.548
I was pleased just by the fact
that he even called me.

00:11:05.748 --> 00:11:08.948
We were already friends, and I was
on the court with him many times,

00:11:09.285 --> 00:11:12.125
but I was on the opposing side.

00:11:12.650 --> 00:11:17.993
And my players, whom I coached,
didn't fare very well.

00:11:19.387 --> 00:11:23.067
When he first called me,
and when I came to my first Wimbledon,

00:11:24.690 --> 00:11:29.790
Marian Vajda helped me then
because we worked together in the beginning.

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:33.696
He introduced me to those things
and how they work.

00:11:35.595 --> 00:11:40.178
I always claimed that people
from the Balkans adapt quickly.

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:43.500
If they dropped us from a plane
on an island,

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:48.180
we would find some players
and form a team.

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:51.951
A Balkan person can coach anyone,
but not everyone can coach

00:11:52.118 --> 00:11:54.038
a person from the Balkans.

00:11:54.207 --> 00:12:00.360
That's my opinion, that's what I think.
We adapt very quickly.

00:12:01.213 --> 00:12:07.057
I agree, I've seen that myself.
Many times.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:12.489
Tell me, did it help you -
you just confirmed it...

00:12:12.788 --> 00:12:17.716
How much did it help that you also played
and were in similar situations?

00:12:19.620 --> 00:12:24.580
My opinion is that in tennis,
there are coaches who never played ATP.

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:28.820
They may not be head coaches.
It's the same in football and tennis.

00:12:29.220 --> 00:12:33.529
You often say that it's enough to see
Novak for five seconds in the morning

00:12:33.651 --> 00:12:36.251
and you immediately know
what your whole day will be like.

00:12:36.816 --> 00:12:40.225
You have that feeling because
you were also a player.

00:12:40.447 --> 00:12:44.722
And that's why you tolerate
some of his reactions -

00:12:45.004 --> 00:12:47.004
when he shouts and yells.

00:12:47.394 --> 00:12:49.746
How much did your playing
experience help you?

00:12:49.904 --> 00:12:52.304
It helped me because...

00:12:53.820 --> 00:13:00.100
First, it helped that we used
to live in the same country.

00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:02.820
And that we speak the same language,
which is very important.

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:06.220
Speed is very important
because I don't have time...

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:10.540
In football, you have halftime
to discuss tactics.

00:13:10.780 --> 00:13:14.020
We also discuss tactics in tennis,
but we only have 10 or 15 seconds

00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:17.460
to tell him something.
He expects that.

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:20.780
The courts are large,
and I don't hear half of what he says,

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:23.860
because people
are shouting behind me.

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:26.820
Then I told him that I know
how he feels on the court -

00:13:27.060 --> 00:13:30.180
because I was a player.
Everything is allowed.

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:33.660
The most important thing
is to win the match.

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:36.900
The result is important.
You can yell if you want.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:41.420
Just don't shout from 200 meters -
come closer so we can communicate.

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:49.905
So that never bothered me,
but it was stressful at the beginning.

00:13:51.163 --> 00:13:55.163
Until I got used to it.
Later, I knew exactly what to say.

00:13:56.151 --> 00:14:00.911
Sometimes he wouldn't hear me,
so I'd tell someone next to me,

00:14:01.181 --> 00:14:05.272
and they'd pass it on to him.
It's just like that.

00:14:05.607 --> 00:14:09.280
He's like that, and he has
to behave like that.

00:14:09.487 --> 00:14:13.260
Although my opinion is that a player
goes on the court alone -

00:14:13.424 --> 00:14:15.002
wins alone or loses alone.

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:22.500
I can't help much as a coach.
But we did what he asked of us.

00:14:22.940 --> 00:14:26.017
And that's why the results are...

00:14:26.418 --> 00:14:30.858
Although, in the end,
he plays alone and decides alone.

00:14:31.620 --> 00:14:35.260
Yes, but he needs help.
You're used to playing alone.

00:14:35.660 --> 00:14:38.947
You said something
interesting a moment ago.

00:14:39.166 --> 00:14:42.366
That a Balkan person can coach anyone,
but a Balkan person can only be

00:14:42.482 --> 00:14:44.602
coached by someone from the Balkans.

00:14:44.711 --> 00:14:48.619
Do you think that people from
the Balkans are specific?

00:14:48.794 --> 00:14:52.119
In what way? Is it physical build,
mentality, or something else?

00:14:52.353 --> 00:14:58.009
It's a combination of everything
mentality, physicality, upbringing,

00:14:59.835 --> 00:15:04.353
how we grew up,
how our parents raised us.

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:11.400
We have a different way of thinking.
I learned a lot from him.

00:15:11.540 --> 00:15:18.420
I wish I could go back to my playing
days and apply some of that knowledge.

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:22.180
He took training to a higher level,

00:15:22.535 --> 00:15:26.995
a higher level of thinking,
a higher level of everything.

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:32.580
But we are unique here.
We have this hunger.

00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:35.700
We came from nothing.

00:15:36.017 --> 00:15:38.897
From being underestimated,
from nothing, from zero,

00:15:39.151 --> 00:15:43.041
and we always had to prove ourselves.
It was always about proving something.

00:15:43.265 --> 00:15:47.698
Look at the man who has won the most
Grand Slam titles in men's tennis,

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:50.280
the greatest player of all time,

00:15:50.553 --> 00:15:53.673
and yet, even today,
he still has to prove himself.

00:15:53.912 --> 00:15:58.127
People question him - 'Is he injured?
Is there something wrong?'

00:15:58.639 --> 00:16:02.799
There's always something...
-It's unfair. -It's unjust.

00:16:02.942 --> 00:16:09.542
It's also a motivation. -Of course,
it is - that's why he's still playing.

00:16:09.926 --> 00:16:14.406
Even during the whole COVID situation
and his stance on things...

00:16:14.709 --> 00:16:21.011
It's always like the whole world is
against him, us, and everything.

00:16:21.392 --> 00:16:23.312
And that drives you.

00:16:23.592 --> 00:16:27.552
It gives you extra motivation,
strength, energy to be better.

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:35.820
You are from the same region,
actually, we are both from

00:16:36.180 --> 00:16:41.140
the same city that,
considering its size,

00:16:41.980 --> 00:16:46.020
has every right to be proud of how
many top athletes it has produced.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:51.180
And at the same time,
it proudly claims to be

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:53.740
the craziest city in the world.

00:16:54.180 --> 00:16:58.980
Let's go back a bit - you started
playing tennis quite early.

00:16:59.260 --> 00:17:05.180
Why tennis? That was in the '80s, a
time when tennis was an elitist sport.

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:08.700
In Split, there was Hajduk
and Jugoplastika,

00:17:08.940 --> 00:17:11.580
water polo was also big because
it was played in the summer

00:17:11.860 --> 00:17:15.060
and had its own popularity and role.
Why tennis? In Firule?

00:17:15.300 --> 00:17:19.820
I was born there, and my grandfather
lived there. -Pošk is there too.

00:17:20.100 --> 00:17:23.060
I learned to swim at Pošk on Zenta.

00:17:23.340 --> 00:17:27.056
I used to jump off that pool
that had the sea below it.

00:17:27.660 --> 00:17:29.627
That's where I grew up.

00:17:29.906 --> 00:17:32.845
On Zenta, I used to do vaterpolo
My father played tennis.

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:37.920
I spent every summer
at my grandparents' house,

00:17:38.144 --> 00:17:41.603
and the tennis courts
were just three meters away.

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:48.620
When I was still in school, people
from Hajduk would come and pick out

00:17:48.980 --> 00:17:52.940
10 or 15 of us, but I think
I chose the right sport.

00:17:53.180 --> 00:17:56.140
Tennis was my first love.

00:17:57.740 --> 00:18:02.104
The moment I picked up that racket,
somehow, I just clicked with it...

00:18:02.244 --> 00:18:04.627
Everyone wanted to play
for Hajduk back then,

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:09.033
and Jugoplastika was dominating...
But for me, tennis was simply it.

00:18:09.243 --> 00:18:12.963
So, your idols weren't
Vujović, Bakaš, Šurjak...

00:18:13.283 --> 00:18:16.729
But Pilić and Franulović?
Or did you not really have idols?

00:18:16.971 --> 00:18:20.947
No, I didn't really have...
Actually, my idol was John McEnroe.

00:18:21.223 --> 00:18:25.103
Of course, Šurjak and the others...

00:18:25.251 --> 00:18:30.666
They were legends, that played for
Hajduk, and that club was everything.

00:18:30.813 --> 00:18:34.693
But I simply chose a different path.

00:18:34.928 --> 00:18:38.502
I wanted to be
an individual athlete...

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:42.174
Maybe I wasn't really
an individualist.

00:18:42.350 --> 00:18:48.588
My father always told me I was 'too
nice' to be number one in the world.

00:18:48.799 --> 00:18:54.199
I was number two. To be number one,
your ego has to be through the roof.

00:18:54.341 --> 00:18:57.181
Because there's always someone
trying to take you down,

00:18:57.319 --> 00:18:59.239
always someone trying to beat you...

00:18:59.449 --> 00:19:02.736
It's a gladiator sport, and that
kind of mindset makes you stronger.

00:19:02.862 --> 00:19:07.799
Maybe I just wasn't ready to be number
one. But I fell in love with tennis,

00:19:08.013 --> 00:19:12.533
and I believe that you're destined
to be good at a certain sport.

00:19:12.649 --> 00:19:14.689
I think I chose the right one.

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:19.260
And in the end, the Split club
produced, as I think you mentioned,

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:21.980
the most top 10 players ever?

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:25.060
Yes, it's a global phenomenon.

00:19:25.340 --> 00:19:31.820
There were Marijančić, Nikola Pilić,
Željko Franulović, Mate Pavić, me,

00:19:33.940 --> 00:19:36.620
Jelena Kostanić, Petra Martić...

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:41.340
But to have five players in the
top 10 from a single club,

00:19:41.470 --> 00:19:44.230
that just had five or six courts...
-That's practically nothing...

00:19:44.369 --> 00:19:46.239
That doesn't exist anywhere else.

00:19:46.394 --> 00:19:51.277
That club should be a museum,
a place where tourists coming to Split

00:19:51.927 --> 00:19:55.847
visit and learn about the players
that were shaped there,

00:19:56.080 --> 00:20:02.207
that came from nothing, from zero.
-I see, that's incredible.

00:20:03.540 --> 00:20:07.180
So, how big of an influence
did your parents,

00:20:07.406 --> 00:20:10.566
especially your father Srđan,
have on you?

00:20:11.900 --> 00:20:14.660
Well, I think his influence
was the greatest.

00:20:14.940 --> 00:20:18.060
My mother was always there too,
holding everything together

00:20:18.340 --> 00:20:21.700
like only a woman can, but he
dedicated himself completely to me.

00:20:21.940 --> 00:20:27.540
He was a university professor who left
his job because he believed in me.

00:20:27.780 --> 00:20:31.203
He told me: 'You're better at what
you do than I am at what I do.'

00:20:33.980 --> 00:20:36.869
Now, think about that...
-Everything he told me about tennis,

00:20:36.935 --> 00:20:38.602
was the only truth I cared for.

00:20:38.744 --> 00:20:41.876
Now, looking back, I realize a lot of
what he said wasn't actually correct.

00:20:41.989 --> 00:20:43.949
But I listened to him.

00:20:44.095 --> 00:20:47.540
To me, he was the Bible of tennis.
-The holy scripture, exactly.

00:20:48.220 --> 00:20:52.660
That's how it was. But an
interesting thing about him...

00:20:53.986 --> 00:20:57.754
No matter where I went,
whichever coach I trained with,

00:20:58.121 --> 00:21:01.035
whichever academy I joined,
he would tell them all,

00:21:01.121 --> 00:21:05.231
'You can change any of his shots,
but don't touch his serve.'

00:21:05.447 --> 00:21:08.114
Come on! -I swear,
he told everyone that.

00:21:08.293 --> 00:21:13.535
'His serve is his. Don't mess with it.
Let him serve however he wants.'

00:21:13.674 --> 00:21:16.034
And this is coming from
a recreational player, right?

00:21:16.274 --> 00:21:19.034
A recreational player
who was a professor at FESB,

00:21:19.198 --> 00:21:23.293
who played decent tennis,
but he saw something in me.

00:21:23.441 --> 00:21:27.841
I mean, no one could have known. Who
could guarantee what I would become...

00:21:28.017 --> 00:21:31.177
And like you said,
it wasn't exactly a cheap sport,

00:21:31.421 --> 00:21:36.501
it had to be paid for,
financed, pushed forward...

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:42.340
And then, at 14, my parents had to
make their first big decision,

00:21:42.860 --> 00:21:46.380
whether I would continue
my education or not.

00:21:46.820 --> 00:21:49.300
Both of them had university degrees,

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:52.900
and back then, you know how things
were... If you didn't go to school,

00:21:53.140 --> 00:21:56.260
people would say, 'This one is...'
-That was the mindset back then.

00:21:56.500 --> 00:22:00.020
'...he is a troublemaker.' -And now,
unfortunately, it's almost the norm.

00:22:00.260 --> 00:22:04.140
Today it's normal, but back then,
it was shameful not to go to school.

00:22:04.460 --> 00:22:09.500
But they decided that
I was special in this sport...

00:22:10.740 --> 00:22:14.340
But then came the reality
of how to finance all of it,

00:22:14.780 --> 00:22:19.300
in the midst of all the craziness...
They even sold the apartment...

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:26.675
Those are the things a young person
like me had to endure.

00:22:32.299 --> 00:22:35.570
Sorry for interrupting, but that's
exactly what I wanted to talk about.

00:22:35.854 --> 00:22:39.586
It's an incredible story,
but not many people know about it.

00:22:39.797 --> 00:22:43.851
This whole thing became serious
when you were about 14.

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:31.941
Like we talked about over lunch,
it's an expensive sport.

00:22:44.780 --> 00:22:51.860
your father sacrificed his career
as a university professor,

00:22:52.380 --> 00:22:58.980
which was his dream. That's a huge
decision... You sold the apartment...

00:23:01.660 --> 00:23:05.860
Then, in 1988, you're 17,
maybe not even that old yet,

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:08.877
when your sister,
unfortunately, falls ill...

00:23:09.171 --> 00:23:15.698
Was that the moment you felt
the full weight of responsibility?

00:23:16.231 --> 00:23:22.112
Not just the idea that it would be
good for you to become successful,

00:23:22.768 --> 00:23:30.510
but that your family's future depended
on you? -Yes. That was it.

00:23:31.340 --> 00:23:33.700
They sent me to Australia,

00:23:34.860 --> 00:23:38.380
and like we talked about before, it
felt like I was one of those refugees

00:23:38.660 --> 00:23:44.300
on a rubber dinghy, just floating
in the middle of the sea...

00:23:44.780 --> 00:23:49.860
Will the dinghy pop? Will I sink?
Or will some ship come and save me?

00:23:50.220 --> 00:23:58.220
I went to Australia - on a plane,
with no money, no plan, nothing.

00:24:00.300 --> 00:24:03.620
And failure was not an option.

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:10.540
In my mind, there was no scenario
where I wouldn't succeed.

00:24:10.632 --> 00:24:12.472
I had to succeed.

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:20.300
It was for my sister.
We needed money for her treatment.

00:24:21.820 --> 00:24:23.860
I didn't even think about myself.

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:27.380
Maybe if I had thought about myself,
I wouldn't have made it.

00:24:27.580 --> 00:24:30.900
Because you would've had options.
-Exactly. If I had other options,

00:24:31.100 --> 00:24:34.079
maybe things would've been different.
But this was it. Mission: Sister.

00:24:34.321 --> 00:24:39.211
Mission: Save her and her health.

00:24:39.408 --> 00:24:44.848
And when I arrived in Australia,
everything just took off.

00:24:45.041 --> 00:24:53.993
My life completely changed there.
-You were 17. Looking back now,

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:58.660
it sounds like a great story,
but at the time...

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:03.220
That's actually the blueprint
for so many champions.

00:25:03.500 --> 00:25:06.877
It either breaks you,
or if you come out of that storm,

00:25:07.159 --> 00:25:11.479
you make it to the top.
That's how you get into the top 10.

00:25:11.667 --> 00:25:15.986
That's how you reach,
what we love to call, 'the throne'.

00:25:16.646 --> 00:25:22.674
And after that, your career
skyrocketed-countless tournaments,

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:31.805
victories, highs, lows, fame,
financial success, all of it...

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:40.100
You became one of the most beloved,
exciting, and admired tennis players.

00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:45.020
But when you look at your
entire career now...

00:25:45.340 --> 00:25:48.517
A person's working life
lasts 50 years,

00:25:48.756 --> 00:25:51.476
but an athlete's career
lasts maybe 20 or 25.

00:25:51.638 --> 00:25:54.438
And in the end,
it's just a handful of moments,

00:25:54.584 --> 00:25:57.345
both positive and negative,
that define everything.

00:25:57.558 --> 00:25:59.868
Like that moment in 1988.

00:26:00.102 --> 00:26:05.173
What are the moments that either
stopped you in your tracks

00:26:05.665 --> 00:26:08.545
or pushed you forward?

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:16.380
From '88 to '89,
when I went to Australia,

00:26:17.220 --> 00:26:20.220
was the time I got a little
push forward in my career,

00:26:20.460 --> 00:26:24.076
and then everything just took off.
By 1990, I was in the top 10.

00:26:25.623 --> 00:26:31.244
That same year, I played
my first Wimbledon semifinal.

00:26:31.823 --> 00:26:37.424
'92 still stings - that Wimbledon
final. I was the absolute favorite.

00:26:38.580 --> 00:26:41.260
I had beaten Lendl,
Edberg, and Sampras,

00:26:41.431 --> 00:26:44.025
and then I lost in five
sets to Agassi.

00:26:44.212 --> 00:26:47.361
No one thought
I would lose, not even me.

00:26:48.786 --> 00:26:54.932
But now, thanks to social media, you
can go back and watch those matches,

00:26:55.199 --> 00:26:58.643
so, I watched them back. And honestly,
he deserved to win that day.

00:26:58.823 --> 00:27:03.143
He played better. It was like
I didn't believe in myself that day.

00:27:03.297 --> 00:27:07.088
I didn't play the way
I should have at that level.

00:27:07.292 --> 00:27:11.057
That's the Wimbledon final, it's like
playing in the World Cup final.

00:27:11.226 --> 00:27:15.885
You have to bring your best,
or the other guy will. -Exactly.

00:27:16.700 --> 00:27:19.740
My career was solid.

00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:26.180
But the biggest drop, when everything
started going downhill, was...

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:30.900
In '98 you guys were in France...
-With Sampras...

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:36.220
...and I was in Wimbledon.
And that support from you guys...

00:27:36.580 --> 00:27:42.180
Things were going
well for both of us.

00:27:42.540 --> 00:27:46.100
I played the final,
and that final broke me.

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:51.020
It crushed me because I truly believe
I was the better player.

00:27:51.300 --> 00:27:56.980
I played better. I should have won.
And I didn't. -Yeah.

00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:02.820
And from that moment on,
everything started going downhill.

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:11.642
If you could replay one match,
which one would it be?

00:28:12.540 --> 00:28:19.340
'92. -'92. -Because if I had won
that final, I think everything

00:28:19.574 --> 00:28:23.114
would have opened up for me.
It would have given me more strength,

00:28:23.282 --> 00:28:25.903
more confidence, and I would
have been a better player.

00:28:26.085 --> 00:28:28.925
I believe I would have won
another Grand Slam. -Yeah.

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:32.980
Maybe I would have even
reached number one. -Yeah.

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:37.060
And now we come to that story,
the one that's been told a 100 times

00:28:37.460 --> 00:28:43.420
but never gets old.
Wimbledon 2001.

00:28:44.820 --> 00:28:51.980
What I want to know is
where did you find the confidence?

00:28:52.460 --> 00:28:54.820
Where did you find the belief to win?

00:28:55.100 --> 00:28:58.740
Because at that time,
you were struggling. -Yes.

00:28:58.862 --> 00:29:01.342
You weren't playing well.

00:29:02.300 --> 00:29:07.940
And before that, there was the whole
story with the rackets from Brighton.

00:29:08.220 --> 00:29:12.140
By the way, since we're
talking about rackets...

00:29:12.660 --> 00:29:16.500
Is it true that the first two rackets
your father bought for you,

00:29:16.820 --> 00:29:21.300
for which he borrowed the money,
you broke both of them?

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:23.580
I did. In three seconds.

00:29:23.987 --> 00:29:26.676
It was a Sunday.
And he even told me:

00:29:26.980 --> 00:29:31.106
'Don't go to practice,
it's a stupid Sunday...'

00:29:31.540 --> 00:29:38.580
And I kept saying, 'I want to go, I'll
be calm...' Yeah, sure, I'll be calm.

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:48.820
He didn't even have time to arrive,
and I had already... -Smashed them?

00:29:49.300 --> 00:29:52.460
Smashed them.
And then the look on his face...

00:29:52.740 --> 00:29:57.500
He didn't know whether to kill me
right then or later.

00:29:58.580 --> 00:30:03.100
The man borrowed money.
He had to pay it back,

00:30:03.380 --> 00:30:08.700
then borrow again to buy me new
rackets so that I, like a lunatic,

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:11.361
could break them again.

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:16.220
It wasn't easy to get
rackets back then.

00:30:16.500 --> 00:30:19.740
And there I was,
breaking them in two minutes.

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:25.340
Honestly, the burden that
he and my mother took on for me,

00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:34.100
that's an unbelievable kind of love
from parents to their child.

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:42.559
But, well, somehow it paid off.
Yes, he has stents and a bypass,

00:30:43.860 --> 00:30:50.396
his health is pretty ruined.
I think they would do it all over again...

00:30:50.904 --> 00:30:54.220
Would they do it all over again?
-I think they would do it all over again.

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:58.780
The road was tough,
but in the end, it all paid off.

00:30:59.020 --> 00:31:05.300
It paid off the most because of 2001.
Before Wimbledon, it was Brighton?

00:31:05.670 --> 00:31:08.670
Something happened that
had never happened before.

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:12.860
End of 2020. -OK. -Sorry, 2000.

00:31:14.300 --> 00:31:17.340
How was it? Tell us.
-I came to Brighton.

00:31:17.940 --> 00:31:22.460
You lived in England. The wind
was blowing, I don't know why I came.

00:31:22.740 --> 00:31:27.740
Actually, I know why I came.
I had to win two rounds in 2001

00:31:28.060 --> 00:31:31.700
to be able to enter the Australian Open.

00:31:35.580 --> 00:31:39.540
I couldn't beat anyone,
literally, I couldn't.

00:31:40.140 --> 00:31:49.192
I came with three rackets. By chance,
I won the first round and broke a racket.

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:53.676
I'm playing the second round.
I know what this match means.

00:31:53.853 --> 00:31:57.413
If I win, I'm in the main draw,
if not, I'm in the qualifiers.

00:31:58.802 --> 00:32:02.842
I already broke one racket
at the start, I have one more left.

00:32:03.178 --> 00:32:08.458
In the third set, 8000 break points,
I don't convert any.

00:32:08.715 --> 00:32:12.035
I mean, I have one more racket.
I knew I had it.

00:32:12.322 --> 00:32:18.922
I thought, should I, shouldn't I?
I say to myself, screw the Australian Open,

00:32:19.460 --> 00:32:24.566
and I smash it. Now there's a problem. This
has never happened in the history of tennis.

00:32:24.786 --> 00:32:27.995
The head referee comes over
and asks me: What do we do?

00:32:28.180 --> 00:32:31.620
Why are you asking me?
You're the head referee.

00:32:31.860 --> 00:32:36.460
He says: I don't know,
we don't have a rule for this.

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:40.829
Can you borrow a racket?
I say: I can't, I won't.

00:32:41.126 --> 00:32:48.258
He says: OK, due to a lack of
equipment, I have to forfeit the match.

00:32:48.976 --> 00:32:55.422
That's how I entered inglorious history.
It is a funny story, though.

00:32:56.454 --> 00:33:01.211
In the end, I played the qualifiers.
I lost in the first round and went back.

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:08.980
Since then, everything started...
-Let's go back to this Wimbledon.

00:33:09.340 --> 00:33:12.500
Objectively, it's tough to win.

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:22.453
Stan Smith said
a phenomenal sentence.

00:33:23.380 --> 00:33:26.860
Experience allows you to
know what you need to do,

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:30.980
and confidence allows you
to actually do it.

00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:34.500
Where did you get your confidence,
your belief in yourself?

00:33:34.940 --> 00:33:36.940
That's a good question.

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:40.660
I think that I...
First, I was in Split.

00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:46.140
I was preparing. At that time,
Hajduk won the championship.

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:50.700
I was in Varaždin,
then I was at the celebration.

00:33:52.220 --> 00:33:57.020
And I'm talking with the team.
Look at this beautiful welcome.

00:33:57.380 --> 00:34:01.100
My friend says that soon
they will welcome me like this too.

00:34:02.340 --> 00:34:05.940
I say, you'll come to pick me up
at the airport when I return.

00:34:06.552 --> 00:34:10.472
No, no, come on. Come on,
it wouldn't be bad.

00:34:10.932 --> 00:34:13.492
To win Wimbledon
and get a welcome like this.

00:34:13.611 --> 00:34:15.408
But, let's not...

00:34:16.395 --> 00:34:21.095
Somehow, during those few weeks
when I was in Varaždin,

00:34:21.337 --> 00:34:27.103
whether Hajduk would win,
all that tension... -It charged you up.

00:34:27.257 --> 00:34:30.137
It charged me up, but still,
it can't charge me up for tennis.

00:34:30.315 --> 00:34:34.115
I was ranked 128th,
and I was playing terribly.

00:34:35.220 --> 00:34:39.420
I know that I arrived in
Hertogenbosch, in the Netherlands.

00:34:39.700 --> 00:34:42.180
I changed my rackets.
You don't change rackets.

00:34:42.540 --> 00:34:49.780
You need to test them for a few months.
My motto is that I can't play worse.

00:34:50.021 --> 00:34:53.390
I can play the same or better.
Worse than this...

00:34:54.240 --> 00:34:56.328
I simply felt...

00:34:59.340 --> 00:35:03.700
Two days before Wimbledon,
the racket I was playing with,

00:35:03.877 --> 00:35:06.192
when I served well,
it made a certain sound.

00:35:06.346 --> 00:35:08.966
I hadn't heard that sound
for a year and a half, two years.

00:35:09.155 --> 00:35:13.005
And then I... -Got it back.
-I got the sound back.

00:35:14.780 --> 00:35:18.420
I said, okay, the sound is there,
I'm playing well.

00:35:18.598 --> 00:35:21.118
My father arrived on Sunday,
he brought newspapers.

00:35:21.327 --> 00:35:26.314
He had never in his life brought me...
-A magazine. -The magazine 'Košarka.'

00:35:27.620 --> 00:35:30.660
I never read it. I knew it existed,
I'd buy it, flip through it.

00:35:30.900 --> 00:35:35.340
He would bring me Sportske and others,
but never that one.

00:35:35.860 --> 00:35:43.180
In the middle, a Dražen poster.
I say, this must be some kind of sign.

00:35:43.860 --> 00:35:46.879
So, in 2001, there's a Dražen
poster in the middle.

00:35:47.066 --> 00:35:49.598
Unfortunately, he's been
gone for a long time.

00:35:49.928 --> 00:35:57.714
It was an anniversary,
because in 1993, unfortunately...

00:35:59.136 --> 00:36:01.582
I put it up on the wall.

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:11.540
I say, he's come to shake me up
and set me straight.

00:36:13.380 --> 00:36:18.820
After the second round,
I felt that I was playing good tennis.

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:25.549
But what can I say? I'm ranked 128th.
I'm happy that I got a wild card,

00:36:26.220 --> 00:36:31.580
an invitation for Wimbledon. Now to say
that I play well every day...

00:36:31.900 --> 00:36:38.580
Each new round was almost, almost.
Until I reached the semifinals.

00:36:38.973 --> 00:36:42.137
How are you playing so well?
Did you improve your serve?

00:36:42.415 --> 00:36:46.546
Is it all in your head? -No, I'm serving well,
moving well. -You feel it? -I feel it.

00:36:46.799 --> 00:36:52.399
I beat Moya, who was a seed,
and Roddick, and Safin, and Rusedski.

00:36:55.180 --> 00:37:01.480
They couldn't break my serve. My serve
brought me back, and everything clicked.

00:37:02.387 --> 00:37:07.207
Now comes the big match against Henman.
For the first time, he's playing a semifinal

00:37:07.413 --> 00:37:11.168
that's not against Sampras.
So, he's basically in the final already.

00:37:11.395 --> 00:37:18.747
I watch the news-Henman Day,
Henman this, finally we have a finalist.

00:37:19.198 --> 00:37:22.966
I think: Slow down,
you'll have the devil instead.

00:37:25.100 --> 00:37:28.903
Then what happened, happened...
-The rain. -With the rain.

00:37:29.220 --> 00:37:34.931
I have to say, the rain saved me.
When the match was interrupted,

00:37:35.255 --> 00:37:39.655
he was simply better than me.
I didn't know what to do.

00:37:40.498 --> 00:37:45.642
That rain came...
It didn't come by accident.

00:37:46.372 --> 00:37:51.673
That's it. -It came with a purpose.
It came at just the right moment.

00:37:53.020 --> 00:37:57.140
That day, I knew- when we
didn't return to the court,

00:37:57.420 --> 00:38:03.180
it was seven in the evening.
Alan Mills, the referee, came,

00:38:03.900 --> 00:38:09.020
he said you're going home.
We continue tomorrow.

00:38:10.300 --> 00:38:13.444
I knew that was it.
I told my coach, that's it.

00:38:13.628 --> 00:38:16.506
We're winning. -That you would win.
-He said: No chance.

00:38:16.641 --> 00:38:20.641
I saw his face the next day.
Every time I stepped on the court...

00:38:20.927 --> 00:38:23.447
And the match kept getting interrupted,
it lasted three days.

00:38:23.624 --> 00:38:26.504
His facial expression
kept getting worse and worse.

00:38:26.744 --> 00:38:30.155
I was getting better,
and he was getting worse.

00:38:31.809 --> 00:38:37.712
It was simply... -Destined.
-Destined. I can't say that

00:38:39.062 --> 00:38:43.759
it was my best tennis. Maybe
I played my best Wimbledon in 1994,

00:38:44.580 --> 00:38:47.300
when I also played the final.

00:38:48.940 --> 00:38:54.140
But I just played my best tennis
at the right moments.

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:58.300
When I needed to, I played well.
When I needed to, I played smart.

00:38:58.540 --> 00:39:01.460
I served well, and when I needed to...
the rain came.

00:39:01.660 --> 00:39:04.780
Something always came
that helped me.

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:11.220
Then I think, now I'm playing my fourth final,
but for the first time on a Monday.

00:39:11.420 --> 00:39:15.100
Maybe that's also a sign.
I've never played a final on a Monday.

00:39:15.340 --> 00:39:19.220
It had only been played on a Monday
maybe four times in Wimbledon history.

00:39:19.420 --> 00:39:24.660
That atmosphere, the madness,
a football-like atmosphere-nothing like tennis.

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:28.860
Somehow, everything... That's...

00:39:30.636 --> 00:39:33.249
I can't say that I
knew I would win,

00:39:33.663 --> 00:39:38.703
but failure was not
an option. -It doesn't exist, yes.

00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:43.860
You won two US Opens,
against Rafter, but this one is mine.

00:39:44.100 --> 00:39:46.620
Mine and no one else's.
-This one is mine,

00:39:46.805 --> 00:39:49.182
and we'll play for 13 days if needed.

00:39:49.371 --> 00:39:53.643
I have to win. -Exactly, that superstition.
A lot of athletes are superstitious.

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:58.300
And I was too. That's often
where you find confidence.

00:39:58.500 --> 00:40:05.020
You mentioned Dražen,
the Wimbledon dedication to Dražen.

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:07.940
The Americans made a film about it.

00:40:08.700 --> 00:40:12.260
It became one of
the 100 greatest sports stories.

00:40:13.100 --> 00:40:16.380
When Leicester won the championship,
that was nothing compared to this.

00:40:16.780 --> 00:40:22.540
Henman, the rain, everything together.
Nadal says he's superstitious,

00:40:22.780 --> 00:40:27.460
but only on the court.
But it means something to a person.

00:40:28.060 --> 00:40:34.500
It strengthens you,
gives you an injection of confidence.

00:40:34.860 --> 00:40:38.460
Exactly. It gives me
a certain calmness.

00:40:38.700 --> 00:40:41.780
I had five or six things...
-Was there something with the urinal?

00:40:42.060 --> 00:40:47.380
The urinal, the parking, the Teletubbies.
But if I hadn't done any of those things,

00:40:47.580 --> 00:40:52.500
I would have thought... Once I did them,
I felt a sense of peace inside.

00:40:52.740 --> 00:40:57.168
I did it in half an hour,
and I said, that's it.

00:40:57.903 --> 00:41:04.692
Now I'm ready to play. Now I'm
ready, so beat me if you can.

00:41:05.657 --> 00:41:09.457
I did my thing...
-That gave you confidence.

00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:17.400
Like Stan Smith used to say. -I couldn't
win based on my ranking.

00:41:18.370 --> 00:41:24.869
In the tournament before Wimbledon,
I lost to an unimportant player.

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:31.420
There was no tennis confidence.
But the poster and all these other things

00:41:31.660 --> 00:41:38.540
gave me all of that, a certain calmness.
When we put it all together,

00:41:39.105 --> 00:41:45.151
we pulled out that confidence.
Day by day, I was getting better,

00:41:45.340 --> 00:41:49.464
believing in myself more and more.
-An impossible story.

00:41:50.420 --> 00:41:53.460
The way we watched it,
an unbelievable story.

00:41:53.660 --> 00:41:57.540
A final on a Monday, a final that
didn't last three, but five sets.

00:41:57.780 --> 00:42:04.600
The fifth set was a whole lifetime,
plus all the mistakes and everything else.

00:42:06.940 --> 00:42:13.820
Then the celebration in Split.
An eternal validation in your own city.

00:42:14.140 --> 00:42:18.940
A reception that even CNN covered,
all of it together.

00:42:19.938 --> 00:42:23.018
Just you and Oliver.
Your celebration

00:42:23.580 --> 00:42:28.417
and the farewell of the great Oliver.
Back then, you said...

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:36.706
You said if you weren't born in Split,
you would be... Is that right?

00:42:37.340 --> 00:42:44.340
Do you think that where you're from
determines how much you'll achieve?

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:47.460
Do you think you would have done
more or less if you were born

00:42:47.740 --> 00:42:51.060
100 meters from Bollettieri's academy?

00:42:52.060 --> 00:42:56.820
I think I would have. Maybe I would have
been a totally different type of person.

00:42:57.060 --> 00:43:01.900
Maybe I wouldn't have...
Split is a tough city.

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:09.475
One day, Split loves you,
and 200,000 people will welcome you.

00:43:10.300 --> 00:43:13.700
The next day, those same 200,000
people will want to kill you.

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:16.780
There was always
someone better than you,

00:43:17.060 --> 00:43:19.860
but their mother didn't
wake them up for practice,

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:23.900
they missed the bus,
or the coach didn't like them.

00:43:24.100 --> 00:43:30.780
Or they liked to drink. -They were
better than you, Kukoč, Rađa, and me.

00:43:33.060 --> 00:43:35.420
But when I was serving
in the middle of summer,

00:43:35.660 --> 00:43:41.005
they were playing picigin
at Firule and Baće.

00:43:41.833 --> 00:43:46.704
Split gave me something
that only Split has.

00:43:47.780 --> 00:43:52.900
We all talk about that defiance.
It's important, but you can't

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:59.155
win just with that. You say
you'll get stubborn and win.

00:43:59.483 --> 00:44:04.220
Split has something special.
It made me...

00:44:04.580 --> 00:44:09.380
I think I became a better
and stronger person.

00:44:09.700 --> 00:44:17.245
Through everything I went through,
and all those people who shaped me

00:44:17.580 --> 00:44:22.260
in tennis, from recreational
players to all the coaches,

00:44:23.060 --> 00:44:30.612
to school, to being unrecognized.
You become tougher, stronger.

00:44:31.396 --> 00:44:36.276
That helped me at that moment
when I was lost.

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:42.460
Then that reward comes,
when you stand before 200,000 people.

00:44:42.900 --> 00:44:46.620
Finally, you've won,
they were waiting for it.

00:44:47.020 --> 00:44:52.020
I understand,
I agree with everything.

00:44:53.020 --> 00:44:58.020
Split is a tough city. People
love you in their own way.

00:44:58.220 --> 00:45:06.740
They love you, but they won't admit it.
Half of them act like they won Wimbledon.

00:45:07.820 --> 00:45:13.100
I remember an anecdote.
This will be interesting.

00:45:13.460 --> 00:45:18.460
Back then, we played for Hajduk.
I was 23-24 years old,

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:28.060
and you were 20-21. That's when
the club at Gripe changed its name.

00:45:29.381 --> 00:45:31.899
It had one name,
then it later changed it.

00:45:32.434 --> 00:45:35.594
The owner decided
there is a dress code.

00:45:35.915 --> 00:45:38.795
And you can't enter
wearing sneakers.

00:45:39.255 --> 00:45:43.375
It wasn't an opening,
just a normal evening.

00:45:44.060 --> 00:45:49.215
I was invited to New York,
London, but this guy at the door

00:45:50.020 --> 00:45:54.676
won't let me in because
I wore sneakers.

00:45:55.013 --> 00:46:00.133
Five minutes later,
a guy walks in wearing a ski suit.

00:46:00.860 --> 00:46:06.716
He would not let Ivanišević in.
-That was just like that.

00:46:10.220 --> 00:46:12.614
But this is Split.
-Yes, this is Split.

00:46:13.078 --> 00:46:17.442
You can't be mad at that.
It's just how it is.

00:46:17.660 --> 00:46:20.020
I turned around and left.

00:46:21.340 --> 00:46:24.780
You said it well.
Split is like that.

00:46:25.060 --> 00:46:27.580
They love you,
but won't say they love you.

00:46:27.860 --> 00:46:30.460
What does he want?
Who is he?

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:35.380
They don't want to tell me
anything because I'm also

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:39.715
from that city, and that's it.
Like: 'Who is he?'

00:46:39.990 --> 00:46:47.066
Who is Inavišević, who is Slaven?
We just have that kind of mindset.

00:46:50.300 --> 00:46:54.918
But when it's needed,
we'll always help.

00:46:55.200 --> 00:46:58.028
When it's tough,
they're there for you.

00:46:58.444 --> 00:47:00.404
To wrap this up...

00:47:01.845 --> 00:47:06.217
Split is best represented
by incredible graffiti.

00:47:06.632 --> 00:47:11.118
Back then, when you won Wimbledon,
the city was on fire.

00:47:11.319 --> 00:47:15.079
Dežulović wrote
a great column back then.

00:47:15.187 --> 00:47:17.930
TV's are flying out of windows,
everything is burning,

00:47:18.049 --> 00:47:19.751
and you can't see the sky.

00:47:19.944 --> 00:47:23.798
In the morning, graffiti appears,
not 'Thank you, Goran,'

00:47:23.970 --> 00:47:27.743
not 'Bravo, Goran,' not
'Goran, you're the king,'

00:47:28.086 --> 00:47:30.642
or anything like that, but:
'Finally!'

00:47:30.838 --> 00:47:34.079
Like: 'Why are you tormenting us?'

00:47:34.277 --> 00:47:37.915
Yes, you've been tormenting us
for 20 years.

00:47:38.419 --> 00:47:42.173
But it's hard for people
to understand some things.

00:47:42.467 --> 00:47:47.110
You have to be born there
and leave that maternity ward

00:47:47.229 --> 00:47:50.150
to get the Split chip.

00:47:53.060 --> 00:47:56.361
Only our people understand that.

00:47:57.423 --> 00:48:01.314
That kind of joke,
with nothing mean-spirited.

00:48:01.598 --> 00:48:03.878
We're just like that.

00:48:04.251 --> 00:48:07.760
Simply put, we're like that,
and only people from there

00:48:07.913 --> 00:48:10.306
can understand and accept it.
-Yes, bravo.

00:48:10.542 --> 00:48:15.702
After that famous Wimbledon,
comes the gentle end.

00:48:15.897 --> 00:48:22.127
Has there been saturation,
injuries, or a mix of both

00:48:23.134 --> 00:48:29.164
that made you leave?
Then in 2020, came the induction...

00:48:29.445 --> 00:48:33.725
the crowning achievement
after the Davis Cup,

00:48:34.202 --> 00:48:37.702
your induction
into the Hall of Fame.

00:48:38.259 --> 00:48:42.257
McEnroe, your idol,
introduced you.

00:48:43.160 --> 00:48:45.680
Would you like
to tell us about that?

00:48:46.660 --> 00:48:50.709
When I was chosen,
there was no greater honor.

00:48:50.934 --> 00:48:53.201
Is that the peak?
-Yes, that's the peak.

00:48:53.435 --> 00:48:58.365
It's like they put me in a museum.
I'm alive, but I'm there.

00:48:58.575 --> 00:49:02.608
When I entered that museum
in Newport Beach,

00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:07.620
it was incredible.

00:49:08.480 --> 00:49:12.647
All the legends were there,
so I asked myself:

00:49:12.744 --> 00:49:15.405
'Did I enter the wrong city
or the wrong museum?

00:49:15.517 --> 00:49:17.467
What am I doing here?'

00:49:17.863 --> 00:49:22.519
Simply put, you feel
honor and pride.

00:49:23.605 --> 00:49:27.613
It's truly an
incredible recognition.

00:49:27.940 --> 00:49:32.380
You must give a speech
in front of everyone.

00:49:32.754 --> 00:49:36.554
And when I spoke,
something incredible happened.

00:49:37.050 --> 00:49:41.555
The sky was dark,
as if rain was coming.

00:49:42.136 --> 00:49:48.644
But suddenly,
everything calmed down.

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:58.528
The sky turned gray,
and I gave my speech.

00:49:58.929 --> 00:50:04.009
There's a timer,
you must speak for six minutes.

00:50:04.163 --> 00:50:07.820
And you didn't prepare it, right?
-I had some notes.

00:50:08.065 --> 00:50:11.632
I don't like preparing speeches,
it never turns out right.

00:50:11.783 --> 00:50:15.093
But I said what I wanted.

00:50:15.245 --> 00:50:18.437
I thanked the people
I needed to thank.

00:50:18.957 --> 00:50:21.505
At one point,
I wanted to thank my sister,

00:50:21.640 --> 00:50:23.928
but I didn't,
so I wouldn't cry.

00:50:24.283 --> 00:50:28.687
But it felt like she did
something up there,

00:50:28.894 --> 00:50:33.058
so it didn't rain.
She let me speak.

00:50:33.786 --> 00:50:38.261
All those people
who shaped my career

00:50:38.751 --> 00:50:44.011
made that moment truly incredible.

00:50:47.816 --> 00:50:56.416
Finally, I admitted
I had done something good.

00:50:59.940 --> 00:51:03.075
So, McEnroe brought you there,
and you played with everyone?

00:51:03.420 --> 00:51:09.060
You played McEnroe, Connors,
Becker, Sampras,

00:51:09.340 --> 00:51:14.780
Agassi, Lendl, Wilander,
Edberg... -Federer, Nadal...

00:51:14.949 --> 00:51:17.349
Yes, all the way to Đokovic?
-I haven't played Đokovic.

00:51:17.582 --> 00:51:22.062
Which one was the toughest
opponent for you?

00:51:25.060 --> 00:51:28.660
The toughest for me
was Sampras.

00:51:29.780 --> 00:51:36.140
That man ruined many
beautiful moments in my life.

00:51:36.780 --> 00:51:40.020
Sleepless nights...
-Was he the best?

00:51:40.820 --> 00:51:45.980
If a tournament were organized now...
It's kind of a silly question.

00:51:46.300 --> 00:51:48.980
If a tournament were held now,
with all at their peak,

00:51:49.220 --> 00:51:52.220
at 25 years old,
without Đokovic,

00:51:52.420 --> 00:51:56.948
since you haven't played him,
who would you bet on?

00:51:57.500 --> 00:52:03.580
It depends on the surface,
then or now.

00:52:04.065 --> 00:52:07.380
Still, Federer and Nadal
are such geniuses,

00:52:07.620 --> 00:52:12.060
they'd adapt to any conditions.

00:52:13.380 --> 00:52:17.561
It's hard to compare eras,
but it wouldn't be easy

00:52:18.033 --> 00:52:26.993
against the great Sampras,
on grass, hard, or clay...

00:52:27.740 --> 00:52:31.620
But I think Nadal
would beat them all.

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:36.540
And if Đokovic is included?
-I think Novak would beat them all.

00:52:37.260 --> 00:52:42.420
Novak would win
because he returns well,

00:52:42.700 --> 00:52:46.260
he adapts to both
fast and slow balls.

00:52:49.020 --> 00:52:54.620
Maybe a tight match, 4-5 sets.

00:52:54.940 --> 00:53:02.140
It's hard to compare eras,
but... -Is he your favorite?

00:53:03.380 --> 00:53:09.100
He marked my career.
Him, Agassi, Courier, Chang.

00:53:09.700 --> 00:53:13.300
I had the honor of playing
Borg, Connors, McEnroe,

00:53:13.500 --> 00:53:20.900
but also Federer and Nadal.

00:53:21.580 --> 00:53:28.580
Sampras, when he does this...
My God! Do you know what he said?

00:53:29.496 --> 00:53:31.599
I read it the other day
and laughed so hard.

00:53:31.917 --> 00:53:35.904
What did Chang say when asked
about Sampras' flaws?

00:53:36.479 --> 00:53:38.474
That he can't cook.

00:53:40.220 --> 00:53:44.300
Well, he's right. And maybe
he knows that too. -Maybe.

00:53:45.700 --> 00:53:49.660
It was a shame I faced him
only in semifinals or finals.

00:53:50.580 --> 00:53:55.740
He'd play terribly early on,
but I never got him then.

00:53:55.980 --> 00:53:58.260
We were top seeds.

00:53:58.940 --> 00:54:01.980
And after that, it was...
Go home.

00:54:02.420 --> 00:54:12.300
Now, as a coach, how do you assess
Đokovic, Nadal and Federer?

00:54:12.740 --> 00:54:19.100
What are their similarities, differences,
and their legacy in tennis?

00:54:20.100 --> 00:54:24.260
These are the three greatest
players ever.

00:54:25.180 --> 00:54:30.700
Maybe I'd compare them like this...
Federer plays the most beautiful tennis.

00:54:31.460 --> 00:54:34.620
Even when he plays badly,
it's a joy to watch.

00:54:34.860 --> 00:54:40.580
Then there's Rafa,
a fighter to exhaustion.

00:54:41.020 --> 00:54:46.820
He's a fighter
who gives his all on the court.

00:54:47.140 --> 00:54:56.700
Winning 14 French Opens -
that will never happen again.

00:54:57.220 --> 00:54:59.900
Not just in tennis,
but in any sport.

00:55:00.140 --> 00:55:02.500
Novak is the most complete
of all three.

00:55:02.740 --> 00:55:05.500
The best, the greatest of all time.

00:55:05.700 --> 00:55:10.300
I'm sorry that in 2023,
he was just 1-2 points away

00:55:10.438 --> 00:55:12.198
from winning Wimbledon.

00:55:12.306 --> 00:55:14.266
Then he would have won all four.

00:55:14.343 --> 00:55:19.205
In 2021, he lost to Medvedev,
didn't play his best.

00:55:19.328 --> 00:55:22.568
But Novak is the most complete.

00:55:24.700 --> 00:55:29.420
At Roland Garros,
Nadal was better.

00:55:29.700 --> 00:55:35.140
But Novak was always
the one who could win all four.

00:55:35.380 --> 00:55:42.060
That Golden Slam,
including the Olympics...

00:55:42.860 --> 00:55:45.740
He is, by far,
the most complete player.

00:55:46.020 --> 00:55:51.860
They pushed each other,
made each other even better.

00:55:52.860 --> 00:55:56.620
Novak came later,
maybe that's why...

00:55:56.860 --> 00:56:00.428
Maybe that's why he's
less appreciated by some.

00:56:03.620 --> 00:56:06.700
And in football, we have
Ronaldo and Messi.

00:56:06.980 --> 00:56:12.220
Before that, Connors,
Borg, McEnroe.

00:56:12.860 --> 00:56:17.140
But what you said about Novak,
I wanted to ask you.

00:56:17.380 --> 00:56:23.260
You said he's treated differently
from Nadal and Federer.

00:56:23.500 --> 00:56:27.020
And that it has to do
with where he's from.

00:56:27.340 --> 00:56:30.820
Did you feel that yourself?

00:56:31.420 --> 00:56:36.658
You mentioned this to Dea
in an interview. -Yes, that's right.

00:56:36.762 --> 00:56:39.814
People say, 'It doesn't matter where
you're from.' How doesn't it matter?

00:56:39.932 --> 00:56:42.900
It matters. Everything matters.

00:56:43.994 --> 00:56:48.077
If Luka Modrić were English,

00:56:48.822 --> 00:56:52.702
he'd be the most expensive
footballer ever.

00:56:53.138 --> 00:56:56.694
Is it just business,
or do they control the media?

00:56:56.885 --> 00:56:58.685
It's not the same.

00:56:59.140 --> 00:57:06.380
One is Swiss, one is Spanish,
then comes a guy from Serbia -

00:57:08.420 --> 00:57:13.140
they don't get it.
How, where did he come from?

00:57:14.860 --> 00:57:18.712
He says what he thinks.

00:57:18.901 --> 00:57:27.730
He says what others think
but won't say.

00:57:28.413 --> 00:57:34.822
He was willing to sacrifice
his career for the vaccine.

00:57:36.387 --> 00:57:40.705
Completely? -Completely.
-He refused to get vaccinated.

00:57:43.092 --> 00:57:53.738
And now, people say that vaccine
caused harm, locked us up for years.

00:57:54.038 --> 00:57:56.019
But he stood by his choice.

00:57:56.372 --> 00:58:01.366
Which top athlete
would sacrifice everything?

00:58:02.335 --> 00:58:06.722
He was trashed
in 100,000 ways.

00:58:07.016 --> 00:58:10.256
I was there with him,
I know everything.

00:58:10.418 --> 00:58:12.898
Why? Because he has
his own opinion.

00:58:13.170 --> 00:58:16.400
He never told anyone
what to do. We all got vaccinated.

00:58:16.602 --> 00:58:18.705
He never said,
'Don't get vaccinated.'

00:58:18.919 --> 00:58:21.879
Never in his life. He organized
a tournament in Belgrade,

00:58:22.010 --> 00:58:24.978
where he arranged vaccination
for other players,

00:58:25.194 --> 00:58:29.119
but he didn't get vaccinated.
And then they condemned him.

00:58:29.694 --> 00:58:34.814
Everything he says is somehow
against the Western world.

00:58:35.460 --> 00:58:38.300
Just because he speaks the truth,
and the truth sometimes hurts.

00:58:38.580 --> 00:58:44.740
People don't want to hear it,
but he never feared saying it.

00:58:45.348 --> 00:58:50.850
I know what others think,
but they wrap it up...

00:58:54.500 --> 00:59:00.555
And of course, we're all from Balkans,
so they put us in a box.

00:59:00.699 --> 00:59:03.483
'You are from the Balkans,
you are this, you are that...'

00:59:03.718 --> 00:59:08.398
But he proved them wrong on the court,
and they can't take that from him.

00:59:10.338 --> 00:59:12.030
He's the best.

00:59:12.396 --> 00:59:16.413
You don't have to like him,
but you have to respect him.

00:59:17.243 --> 00:59:23.777
Eventually, they had to acknowledge him.
Because he's the greatest.

00:59:24.246 --> 00:59:27.373
If he were one of the other two,
they would have already done it.

00:59:27.640 --> 00:59:30.303
But that's what we talked about.

00:59:30.440 --> 00:59:32.994
Sometimes, that works
to your advantage.

00:59:33.099 --> 00:59:36.216
It pushes you even harder,
what we call 'grinta' down here.

00:59:36.320 --> 00:59:39.051
And then you show them
what you can do. -Yes, exactly.

00:59:39.213 --> 00:59:44.903
And there's also business in it.
-Sport has become one big business.

00:59:45.273 --> 00:59:48.942
We used to say sports
were free of politics,

00:59:49.168 --> 00:59:52.368
but now... That's where
it's the most.

00:59:52.460 --> 00:59:57.890
For three years, politics decided
what you could say, where you could go.

00:59:57.999 --> 01:00:00.092
If you weren't vaccinated,
you were cast aside.

01:00:00.216 --> 01:00:02.179
Like in that movie,
Battle on the Neretva.

01:00:02.340 --> 01:00:04.686
'Let's go, brothers, step aside.'

01:00:05.989 --> 01:00:12.069
Football is the biggest sports business.
-That's the world today.

01:00:12.860 --> 01:00:16.220
100,000 competitions,
everyone wants to profit.

01:00:17.340 --> 01:00:22.580
So it's a business,
and that's how we must act.

01:00:23.420 --> 01:00:26.902
We can talk all we want,
we can even love the game.

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:28.964
Yes, we grew up
in a different time.

01:00:29.055 --> 01:00:30.761
But that's how it is now.

01:00:30.871 --> 01:00:32.838
Times have changed,
and we must adapt.

01:00:32.959 --> 01:00:34.799
Yes, that's just how it is.

01:00:35.317 --> 01:00:41.372
These two are from Switzerland
and Spain, and he's from Serbia.

01:00:42.270 --> 01:00:44.190
And it's about money.

01:00:44.580 --> 01:00:47.821
Now they're global stars,
but it's different when

01:00:48.120 --> 01:00:55.175
Iva Majoli wins Roland Garros
and when Raducanu wins the US Open.

01:00:55.700 --> 01:00:59.300
﻿There's half a billion
pounds is involved.

01:01:00.100 --> 01:01:06.780
And that's true, but it's also motivation
for the little people. -That's true.

01:01:10.529 --> 01:01:14.700
For me, it was an honor
and a responsibility

01:01:15.020 --> 01:01:18.100
to coach such a man.
To be close to him,

01:01:18.420 --> 01:01:27.305
learn from him, and watch
all the records he achieved.

01:01:28.140 --> 01:01:35.575
There were difficult moments,
but when you sum it up,

01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:39.900
there were far more
beautiful and successful ones.

01:01:40.220 --> 01:01:44.420
But it was an honor and a privilege
for him too that you were his coach.

01:01:48.020 --> 01:01:50.980
So, a wonderful career...

01:01:51.340 --> 01:01:55.866
and one of the most beloved
and charismatic players.

01:02:00.220 --> 01:02:10.460
But when I analyze you,
you're seen more as a Maverick.

01:02:12.460 --> 01:02:18.020
When you say "Ivanišević", the first
thought is a positive madman.

01:02:18.260 --> 01:02:21.900
Everyone loves him, and it's never
boring to read his interviews

01:02:22.220 --> 01:02:24.740
or watch him on TV. That's it.

01:02:25.780 --> 01:02:28.580
It is silly to say that
you are underestimated.

01:02:29.620 --> 01:02:36.220
But, in the context of your career,
more was said about what you

01:02:36.500 --> 01:02:41.500
could have done but didn’t.
As Tiriac said when he saw you:

01:02:41.700 --> 01:02:44.020
"This little guy will win
the Wimbledon championship."

01:02:44.300 --> 01:02:47.420
He didn't win five, but he won one.
And you gave it your all.

01:02:47.660 --> 01:02:53.820
For so many years, you were
the world's No. 2 player.

01:02:54.220 --> 01:03:00.420
You won Wimbledon, the Davis Cup,
and two Olympic medals.

01:03:01.100 --> 01:03:03.900
You entered the Hall of Fame.
What's next?

01:03:04.100 --> 01:03:07.420
And everyone sees the glamour,
summer vacations on a yacht.

01:03:07.620 --> 01:03:11.100
But they don't see the work,
the sacrifice, the preparation...

01:03:11.820 --> 01:03:19.380
Yes, that's unfortunately true.
Goran has broken so many rackets.

01:03:19.620 --> 01:03:22.260
Goran and his serve...

01:03:22.900 --> 01:03:26.700
But I was world No. 2
in an individual sport.

01:03:26.980 --> 01:03:29.420
You're alone there,
it's a gladiatorial sport.

01:03:29.551 --> 01:03:32.631
Alone, and for you,
there's no substitute.

01:03:32.752 --> 01:03:35.005
No one asks how
you are on that day.

01:03:35.084 --> 01:03:37.615
Did I sleep well?
Is something hurting me?

01:03:39.860 --> 01:03:43.780
I wasn't crazy, as people say.

01:03:46.530 --> 01:03:52.336
You can't be mentally weak
and be No. 2 in the world.

01:03:52.980 --> 01:03:55.860
Nothing happens just like that.

01:03:55.982 --> 01:03:59.240
You said you were crazy,
so it had some impact.

01:03:59.365 --> 01:04:01.157
Yes, three Gorans...

01:04:02.700 --> 01:04:10.001
I calmed down a bit
with that Wimbledon story.

01:04:12.060 --> 01:04:18.500
I put the "three Gorans"
in the spotlight.

01:04:18.820 --> 01:04:25.121
And that story is still
relevant 24 years later.

01:04:25.769 --> 01:04:31.304
The three Gorans are still alive.
That's incredible.

01:04:32.860 --> 01:04:39.860
It's fascinating. I lost many
matches for no reason.

01:04:40.180 --> 01:04:43.860
I fought myself
in many matches.

01:04:44.180 --> 01:04:53.189
But I wouldn't be who I am
if I were really mentally ill.

01:04:53.421 --> 01:04:57.400
That's right,
there was a lot of training.

01:04:57.660 --> 01:05:02.740
Ferrer says,
"There's no shortcut in five sets."

01:05:02.885 --> 01:05:04.805
You have to be ready.

01:05:05.049 --> 01:05:09.794
I remember us talking during lunch,
about how much you trained.

01:05:09.983 --> 01:05:12.543
The stairs on Marjan became
popular with Boško Čavka,

01:05:12.728 --> 01:05:14.685
your fitness coach.

01:05:14.854 --> 01:05:18.974
I don't know much about it.

01:05:19.950 --> 01:05:24.780
Some Hajduk players-
Stipe Andrijašević,

01:05:25.060 --> 01:05:28.700
Ante Miše, and Španjić,
they could run endlessly.

01:05:29.020 --> 01:05:31.100
They were the best runners
with Drago Čelić.

01:05:31.380 --> 01:05:36.460
They also trained with Boško.
They could run up those stairs.

01:05:36.740 --> 01:05:40.140
Allegedly, they said
you did it two or three times.

01:05:40.420 --> 01:05:43.500
Yes, Boško and I
invented those stairs.

01:05:43.780 --> 01:05:51.780
Even today, many don’t believe
the record is unbeaten.

01:05:52.060 --> 01:05:55.969
No one came close to me.

01:05:56.741 --> 01:05:59.701
But those were tough trainings...

01:06:00.038 --> 01:06:03.219
He kicks you out of the car:
"Come on!"

01:06:03.512 --> 01:06:06.883
They threw me out
in front of schools...

01:06:07.749 --> 01:06:12.538
"Go to the hill, see that plain,
then those 300+ stairs!"

01:06:12.797 --> 01:06:14.891
It was a full circle.

01:06:15.941 --> 01:06:19.541
That is all Marjan.
-And that's it.

01:06:19.875 --> 01:06:27.852
You'll be up there in a set time,
then back down to do it again.

01:06:28.820 --> 01:06:31.860
I couldn't say: "I'm tired!"

01:06:33.220 --> 01:06:37.140
I said many times...
I felt sick to my stomach.

01:06:37.500 --> 01:06:41.620
Coach says: "Go throw up!"
-And keep going.

01:06:42.540 --> 01:06:49.300
Now, he immediately sits down,
gets water and energy drinks.

01:06:49.540 --> 01:06:56.540
What energy drinks?
It was running on Marjan.

01:06:56.940 --> 01:07:03.540
You meet someone and
go to the Institute and back.

01:07:04.660 --> 01:07:07.940
Let's go along the trim track.

01:07:08.220 --> 01:07:15.300
So, I didn't think about it...
if I stepped wrong, hurt my leg.

01:07:16.100 --> 01:07:21.060
It could happen, but I never
thought about that. -It's crazy.

01:07:21.780 --> 01:07:27.220
But your father instilled
that in you as a child.

01:07:27.580 --> 01:07:33.900
If he wasn’t satisfied with training,
he'd tell you to walk home.

01:07:34.500 --> 01:07:41.580
He'd go by car, and you
had to get home first. -Yes.

01:07:41.980 --> 01:07:44.820
But no, not during training,
only when I went overboard

01:07:45.100 --> 01:07:52.166
with my craziness. Because he
didn't know what to do with me.

01:07:52.337 --> 01:07:55.236
Then he’d say: "Come on,
get home before me!"

01:07:55.620 --> 01:08:00.300
He starts the car,
and I run along the waterfront.

01:08:00.540 --> 01:08:03.817
Back then, if someone saw you
walking fast, they’d say:

01:08:03.966 --> 01:08:05.864
"Look at this one!"

01:08:08.580 --> 01:08:19.461
I sprinted like crazy
through the city.

01:08:24.300 --> 01:08:26.500
I had to arrive before him.

01:08:27.260 --> 01:08:30.300
So, there was no other option?

01:08:30.860 --> 01:08:36.500
I just didn’t know if he had left,
or was coming back,

01:08:36.900 --> 01:08:42.980
or if he really went home.
I was just running...

01:08:43.740 --> 01:08:53.380
I neither heard nor saw anyone.
People called, waved... but no...

01:08:53.620 --> 01:08:57.940
"Not now, my friend!"
-God, that's terrible.

01:09:01.100 --> 01:09:08.220
How were you for training?
Would you train Goran? -Yes.

01:09:09.300 --> 01:09:16.620
Which coaches do you remember?
-I remember all the old coaches.

01:09:16.900 --> 01:09:23.820
Old Mr. LAci, who taught me...
-Kačer? -The late Zoran Ilić...

01:09:26.020 --> 01:09:30.620
There was also aunt Vera,
who helped with tournaments.

01:09:33.980 --> 01:09:42.820
Then, there was Bob Brett,
who was like a father to me.

01:09:43.100 --> 01:09:48.980
He said you were like a son to him.
-He taught me more than just tennis.

01:09:50.020 --> 01:09:53.780
He taught me how to treat
those who help me.

01:09:54.180 --> 01:09:56.420
Every training,
give something to the masseuse.

01:09:56.740 --> 01:09:59.435
"Give him something,
tell him thank you!"

01:09:59.740 --> 01:10:02.540
Because those people
will appreciate it.

01:10:05.260 --> 01:10:08.980
We had disagreements,
but I was great for coaching.

01:10:09.260 --> 01:10:12.780
I could train all day.
Run and play...

01:10:13.260 --> 01:10:16.220
There were no problems with me.

01:10:16.460 --> 01:10:20.380
That's why I’d love
to train that Goran.

01:10:20.900 --> 01:10:24.860
I think that Goran
would be a better player.

01:10:26.060 --> 01:10:31.340
To pass on the experience
I have to him.

01:10:31.540 --> 01:10:34.700
What would you change?

01:10:35.340 --> 01:10:41.940
During matches,
to behave a little differently.

01:10:43.460 --> 01:10:50.020
To be a little more positive
and work harder on some things.

01:10:50.300 --> 01:10:56.517
It wasn’t all about the serve.
Maybe I would train differently.

01:10:57.119 --> 01:11:03.140
Before, there were no weights
because the doctor forbade it.

01:11:06.260 --> 01:11:10.420
I remember Boško and I hid,
so my father wouldn’t see us.

01:11:10.740 --> 01:11:14.380
Because weights would
slow me down.

01:11:14.700 --> 01:11:16.660
Yes, that’s how it used to be.

01:11:17.340 --> 01:11:24.500
They thought I couldn't be a coach
because I was too nervous.

01:11:24.820 --> 01:11:29.140
How could I coach someone?
And yet, I’m the calmest coach ever.

01:11:34.460 --> 01:11:40.580
Bob Brett is old school. He demands
things be done his way.

01:11:41.100 --> 01:11:45.580
So we sometimes had disagreements.
He coached Harry Hopman,

01:11:45.900 --> 01:11:50.260
the greatest Australian coach.
He trained Rod Laver, Ken Rosewall.

01:11:51.100 --> 01:11:53.700
And he was strict.

01:11:53.935 --> 01:11:59.559
You must communicate with the player
and be five steps ahead.

01:11:59.692 --> 01:12:02.738
Sometimes he thinks you're right,
but you're already...

01:12:02.980 --> 01:12:07.559
You know that best. You have
more players, I have one.

01:12:07.780 --> 01:12:15.711
If only I had communicated more...
but it wasn’t like that before.

01:12:15.916 --> 01:12:18.454
You had to do what you were told.

01:12:18.695 --> 01:12:21.375
The results came,
so I didn’t protest much.

01:12:21.624 --> 01:12:25.944
But there must be communication
between coach and player.

01:12:26.420 --> 01:12:31.340
Your relationship is complicated.
I thought about that in tennis.

01:12:40.140 --> 01:12:43.340
It’s a direct connection
between you and the player.

01:12:43.620 --> 01:12:48.140
There’s no club president
or director hiring me.

01:12:48.380 --> 01:12:50.660
It's just you and me.

01:12:50.940 --> 01:12:54.580
No 20 players where I can say:

01:12:55.260 --> 01:12:59.807
"It's not the best,
but five are improving."

01:13:00.128 --> 01:13:02.980
No, it’s direct and exact.

01:13:03.660 --> 01:13:07.100
Did you help me or not?

01:13:08.580 --> 01:13:13.233
It’s an intense, daily relationship.

01:13:13.725 --> 01:13:18.900
No one shouts from the stands:
"Goran, go!"

01:13:19.740 --> 01:13:23.740
There’s none of that,
but everything is clear between us.

01:13:25.060 --> 01:13:30.500
He hired me.
Some president brought you.

01:13:32.100 --> 01:13:36.180
You answer to Boban, then to Šuker.
-I answer to him.

01:13:36.420 --> 01:13:40.130
To the player who hired me.

01:13:41.645 --> 01:13:48.692
Some are patient, some are not.
We don’t have a magic wand.

01:13:50.739 --> 01:13:56.438
Coaching Novak, he said:
"Finals aren’t enough.

01:13:56.558 --> 01:13:58.238
Finals are a failure."

01:13:58.409 --> 01:14:02.247
In Madrid, if you don’t win,
they wave white handkerchiefs.

01:14:02.460 --> 01:14:05.060
"Goodbye, my friend!"

01:14:05.278 --> 01:14:15.403
There will be a final, but we lost.
He didn’t win, but we are a team.

01:14:16.620 --> 01:14:21.534
If you don’t win the tournament,
it’s a bad tournament.

01:14:22.180 --> 01:14:28.020
I don’t have a problem with pressure.
You're right about that.

01:14:28.340 --> 01:14:33.568
He is the biggest
and he is where he is.

01:14:36.980 --> 01:14:45.428
But in training every day,
and in the match, with all the noise...

01:14:46.625 --> 01:14:50.460
That’s my favorite.

01:14:52.300 --> 01:14:56.540
It’s a match. I can’t do anything
spectacular there.

01:14:56.820 --> 01:15:00.980
Just support him or say something
at the right moment.

01:15:01.420 --> 01:15:04.580
If he hears me,
or I hear him through the noise.

01:15:04.860 --> 01:15:07.980
But we are close in training.

01:15:08.260 --> 01:15:14.620
He disagrees on something,
and I do too. -It’s your interaction.

01:15:15.180 --> 01:15:20.100
Sometimes it was bad,
but in the end, it turns out well.

01:15:20.340 --> 01:15:23.900
That’s all for now.

01:15:26.540 --> 01:15:30.340
The second part of the conversation
is in the next show.

